The creation of a DateTime-object from the input-string keeps the given timezone information. However, in the comparison the DateTime-object is first output to a timestamp, which is then converted to a string with the date()-function. But because a timestamp does not include timezone information, date() will assume the system's timezone. So if the system timezone set in the PHP settings is UTC, a string with another timezone, e.g. 2015-04-24T21:11:00+02:00, will fail to be validated. The result from the date()-function in this example is 2015-04-24T19:11:00+00:00, which is a different string then the input. The DateTime-class has also an option to create a string from a format, DateTime->format(). So it is possible to skip the use of the date()-function with the added benefit that using format() does have access to the timezone information and thus produces the expected 2015-04-24T21:11:00+02:00 to compare with the given input.This commit changes the Rule to accommodate this and expands the tests. Intercept throwables in the Call ruleThe callable defined to the Call rule may also throw an exception andnas we don't want to have errors nor exceptions that are not part of thenValidation during the validation of inputs it just makes sense tonintercept any instance of Throwable.nnThis change was initially thought of because in Travis the version 7.4nof PHP was throwing Error instead of triggering PHP errors which madenthe tests fail.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Also a few changes were made to make the rulena bit simpler.nnThe method getEmailValidator() which was a lazy load of thenEmailValidator class was removed in favor of trying to create theninstance of EmailValidator in the constructor of Email. That makesnthe rule immutable after its creation.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Change how Sf rule worksInstead of creating the Symfony constraints itself Sf accepts anninstance of SymfonyComponentValidatorConstraint.nnCreating objects inside a rule, specially from an external library,nmakes the rule too complex and also limits the possibilities with thenSf rule since Symfony allows users to create complex validations (evennthought their API is not as simple as ours).nnThis commit also simplifies the way the messages are passed from Symfonynto the Sf when only one constraint has failed; instead of passingnthe message of the whole constraint violation list, only the fistnconstraint violation message it passed.nnThe problem that this rule will always have is that when using Not toninvert the validation we have a way to get a proper message sincenSymfony Validator only return the result of constraints that failed.nThat's something the RespectValidation does in a similar way and tonchange it a lot has to be changed.nnThese changes were checked in symfony/validator 4.0 and the versionnwas added to the composer.json file.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Fix wrong behavior of Date ruleThe validation was considering 99 as a valid month and neitherndate_parse_from_format() [1] or DateTime::createFromFormat() [2] wouldncomplain about that.nnThe solution for that was to use checkdate() [3] to verify whether thendate is valid or not. Create FilteredValidationException classAll the classes that were extending AbstractFilterRule were throwingnexceptions that were extending AlphaException. That can cause somenissues when the user has a validation chain with Alpha and anothernchild of AbstractFilterRule and expects AlphaException specifically.nnThis commit creates FilteredValidationException that can be used asnthe parent of the exceptions thrown by rules that extend the classnAbstractFilterRule.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Do not accept whitespace by default in Alpha ruleThe intent of the Alpha rule is to validate alphabetic values.nHowever, it also considers any whitespace character (by default). Thatncauses some confusion, and unless you check its code or tests, you wouldnnever expect that behavior.nnBecause of that confusion, I decided to make Alpha to not considernwhitespace characters as valid, and since in the constructor of thisnrule it's possible to add extra characters to the validation it makesnsense to let the user decide whether they want whitespaces, tabs, newnlines, etc. or not.nnThis rule, as the same as Alnum previously, extendsnAbstractCtypeRule pretty much to only make it easier to consider anynwhitespaces as valid, therefore I saw no reason to keep extending it.nNow Alpha extends the AbstractFilterRule which is the parent ofnAbstractCtypeRule.nnI also took the opportunity to apply our contribution guidelines tonAlpha since we want to apply that to all the rules.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Do not accept whitespace by default in Digit ruleThe Digit rule is meant to validate digits. However, by default, itnalso considers any whitespace character (spaces, new lines, tabs, etc)nas valid.nnSince the rule also accepts a list of characters to ignore during thenvalidation it seemed logical to me to leave the responsibility ofnallowing whitespace characters on the hands of the one who uses thenrule.nnThe messages of the exception are not really consistent, this commitnwill also fix that.nnIt's also clear that the AbstractCtypeRule is an unnecessary overheadnsince it is only a proxy for AbstractFilterRule. That one can andnshould even be removed after this commit is applied especially becausenthis commit will also remove the method filterWhiteSpaceOption whichnis the only substantial difference between AbstractCtypeRule andnAbstractFilterRule.nnThis commit will also apply our guidelines to the Digit rule since wenwant to do that to all the rules we have.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Make the ranges of emoji more accurateThe new ranges are now 100% accurate by not including any Unicode pointnthat is not defined into the reference file.nnFor example, in the old ranges there is this interval:nn[u00{3297}-u00{3299}]nnThat is not accurate because there is no 3298 Unicode point in thenspecs. It may be used by another character and it will cause the checknto fail if the user included that particular character.nnThe new ranges for that previous example are now:nnu00{3297}nu00{3299}nnAnd so on...nnThis commit will make the ranges more accurate with maximum tolerance tonother charcters and also rename the constant name from GROUPS tonRANGES since they are ranges, not groups.n

Improve message when nested Not rules failWhen using nested Not and AllOf rules Validation does not fetch thenmessage of the rule that failed, and instead it fetches the defaultnmessage in AllOfException.nnThat is because Not cannot reach the rules inside AllOf, making itnimpossible to fetch the correct message.nnThis commit will improve that a bit but making Not deal directly withnthe rule inside AllOf when it has only one rule.nnUnfortunately, it will not fix all the issues. For example, when thennegated rule is an AllOf with multiple rules and it fails Not willnfetch only the first message.nnSigned-off-by: Henrique Moody <henriquemoody@gmail.com>n

Improve how to customize the FactoryThe constructor of Factory has three arguments and, even though nonenof them are needed, they are all required.
